769. At the close of the second Punic War, Scipio (the great Africanus) obtained the aid of Masinissa, Numidian prince, against Syphax, king of the western Numidians. After buming Syphax’s camp, Masinissa and the Roman legatus Laelius pursued him to Cirta and took him prisoner. This was in ²03 Β. c.

770. Hasdrubal, brother of Hannibal, marched (207 8.(3.) into Italy to join his brother; but was met by the Romans and defeated at the famous battle of Metaurus, where his army and camp were anni- hilated.

Livy says (XXVII. 49) that when he found all was lost, he spurred his horse into the midst of a Roman cohort, and, as was worthy of Hamilcar’s son and H annibal’s brother, died fighting.

Ovid puts the suicide in a slightly different form.

773. There were three temples of Fors Fortuna at Rome: this one, founded by Servius Tullius (according to tradition), was on the right bank of the Tiberz at the sixth milestone. The festival was 24 June, and it was, as we see, a day os merry-making among the lower classes and slaves.
